During this AB, Ruth made a valiant effort to catch Judge's long foul, crashing into the RF concrete wall with full force.  He lay motionless on the grass while players rushed to his aid and policeman kept back the crowd.  Doc Woods ran up with a water bucket and medical bag.  Ruth had the wind wind knocked out of him and his left hip was badly bruised. Limping badly, he insisted on resuming his position despite Huggins' suggestion for a substitute.1924WS1.EVA.regular.comment.csv"
The cheers for Ruth as he came to bat increased when he ran out the double in obvious pain.1924WS1.EVA.regular.comment.csv"

$When the game ended, excited fans poured on the field and surrounded Ump Holmes.  While one fan shook his finger at the umpire another struck him in the face, knocking him against a wall.  Ump Moriarty, players, and police came to the rescue.  A crowd of several thousands was then dispersed by a squad of blucoats.1924WS1.EVA.regular.comment.csv"

Diving try by McNeely; Ump Evans first ruled it a catch so Collins had to retreat back to 1B, but when McNeely got to his feet without the ball, Evans reversed the decision and Collins was forced out. The White Sox played the rest of the game under protest and formally filed one with the league office after the game.1924WS1.EVA.regular.comment.csv"
